ext{A vector space is a set of vectors that is closed under addition and scalar multiplication.}
ext{It must satisfy the following axioms:}
ext{1. Commutativity of addition: u + v = v + u}
ext{2. Associativity of addition: (u + v) + w = u + (v + w)}
ext{3. Existence of additive identity: there exists a vector 0 such that u + 0 = u}
ext{4. Existence of additive inverse: for each vector u, there exists a vector -u such that u + (-u) = 0}
ext{5. Distributivity of scalar multiplication over vector addition: a(u + v) = au + av}
ext{6. Distributivity of scalar multiplication over scalar addition: (a + b)u = au + bu}
ext{7. Scalar multiplication is associative: (ab)u = a(bu)}
ext{8. Existence of multiplicative identity: 1u = u}

ext{The determinant of a matrix A is equal to the determinant of its transpose A^T. This can be proven using the definition of the determinant and the properties of matrix multiplication.}
ext{Let A be an n	imes n matrix, and let A^T be its transpose.}
ext{Then}
ext{det(A) = }\sum_{\sigma\in S_n} 	ext{sgn}(\sigma) \prod_{i=1}^{n} a_{i,\sigma(i)}
ext{det(A^T) = }\sum_{\sigma\in S_n} 	ext{sgn}(\sigma) \prod_{i=1}^{n} a^T_{\sigma(i),i}
ext{= }\sum_{\sigma\in S_n} 	ext{sgn}(\sigma) \prod_{i=1}^{n} a_{\sigma(i),i}
ext{= det(A)}.

	ext{Let } A 	ext{ be a triangular matrix. By definition, } A = (a_{ij}) 	ext{ for } i, j \in \mathbb{N}. 	ext{Since } A 	ext{ is triangular, either all elements above the main diagonal are zero, or all elements below the main diagonal are zero.}
	ext{Now, let's consider the formula for the determinant of a matrix: }\det(A) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (-1)^{i+j} a_{ij} M_{ij}. 	ext{We can see that the formula involves only elements from the main diagonal and the determinant of sub-matrices formed by excluding the i-th row and j-th column.}
	ext{Since } A 	ext{ is triangular, } a_{ij} = 0 	ext{ for } i > j 	ext{ or } i < j. 	ext{Therefore, only terms involving elements from the main diagonal will contribute to the determinant.}
	ext{Let } D 	ext{ be the diagonal matrix formed by taking the diagonal elements of } A. 	ext{Then, } D = (d_{ij}) 	ext{ with } d_{ij} = a_{ii} 	ext{ if } i = j 	ext{ and } 0 	ext{ otherwise.}
	ext{We can see that } D 	ext{ has the same determinant as } A 	ext{ because their determinants involve the same diagonal elements.}
\det(D) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} d_{ii} = \prod_{i=1}^{n} a_{ii} = \det(A).
